.Dd June 14, 2026
.Dt LANDSTRIP 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm landstrip
.Nd run a command inside an OS-level sandbox
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl -debug
.Op Fl -format Ar format
.Op Fl -error-fd Ar fd
.Op Fl p Ar policy
.Op Fl -policy Ar policy
.Ar command
.Op Ar argument ...
.Nm
.Fl V
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
loads a policy, lowers the sandbox configuration into the platform sandbox
model, applies that sandbox, and then executes
.Ar command .
If no policy file is specified, the policy document is read from standard
input.
.Pp
The accepted policy format is the subset of Anthropic Sandbox Runtime
settings that
.Nm
uses. Unknown fields are ignored.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -debug
Enable debug logging.
.It Fl -format Ar format
Select the policy format. The accepted values are
.Va json
and
.Va yaml .
The default is
.Va json .
.It Fl -error-fd Ar fd
Write landstrip error response blocks to the already-open file descriptor
.Ar fd .
The descriptor must be 3 or greater. On Linux, filesystem denials observed by
the seccomp broker are emitted using the same field format as formatted
standard-error responses. The option is best-effort on backends that do not
expose per-access denial callbacks.
.It Fl p Ar policy , Fl -policy Ar policy
Read a policy file. This option may be repeated. Later policy arguments
are merged over earlier policy arguments. Object values are merged recursively,
arrays are concatenated without duplicates, and scalar values replace earlier
values. Commas are literal filename characters.
.It Fl V , Fl -version
Print version information and exit.
.It Fl h , Fl -help
Print usage information and exit.
.El
.Sh POLICY
The relevant policy shape is:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
{
  "filesystem": {
    "allowWrite": [".", "~/.cargo"],
    "denyWrite": [".git/hooks"],
    "denyRead": ["~/.ssh"],
    "allowRead": ["~/.ssh/config"]
  },
  "network": {
    "httpProxyPort": 8080,
    "socksProxyPort": 8081,
    "allowLocalBinding": false,
    "allowUnixSockets": ["/run/user/1000/agent.sock"],
    "allowAllUnixSockets": false
  }
}
.Ed
.Pp
When
.Fl -format Ar yaml
is used, path fields can also be written as one statement per non-empty line:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
filesystem:
  allowWrite: |
    .
    ~/.cargo
  denyRead: |
    ~/.ssh
  allowRead: |
    ~/.ssh/config
network:
  allowNetwork: true
.Ed
.Pp
Relative sandbox paths are resolved against the directory where
.Nm
was started. Absolute paths are used as-is. The
.Sq ~
and
.Sq ~/
prefixes resolve to the current user's home directory.
Path entries use the same syntax as the macOS sandbox runtime: absolute paths,
relative paths, and gitignore-style
.Sq * ,
.Sq ** ,
.Sq ? ,
and character-class globs. Glob patterns are resolved when the sandbox is
created and therefore follow the same snapshot semantics as other paths.
.Pp
Write access is denied by default. The
.Va allowWrite
paths are granted. The
.Va denyWrite
paths are subtracted by traversing the current directory tree and allowing only
the remaining roots.
.Pp
Read access remains unrestricted when
.Va denyRead
is empty. When
.Va denyRead
contains entries, read access is lowered to an allowlist by traversing from
.Pa /
and subtracting denied paths. Entries in
.Va allowRead
are then added back to the read allowlist.
.Pp
For TCP port rules,
.Nm
uses Landlock TCP port rules and a seccomp user-notification broker for
address-level decisions. When the sandbox is applied, direct TCP connections are
denied by default.
.Pp
.Va httpProxyPort
and
.Va socksProxyPort
select local HTTP and SOCKS proxy ports. Connections to these ports are allowed
only on loopback addresses.
.Nm
does not start proxies or set proxy environment variables; the caller supplies
those when needed. Domain filtering is likewise a caller/runtime responsibility.
Direct TCP remains denied except for configured proxy ports.
Other settings are ignored.
.Pp
On Windows, TCP proxy-port filtering is not yet implemented. Policies that
request proxy ports or local binding are rejected before launch. The Windows
backend runs without network capabilities when no TCP access is requested.
.Pp
.Va allowUnixSockets
permits pathname Unix socket
.Xr connect 2
and
.Xr bind 2
operations under listed paths. Relative paths are resolved against the
sandboxed process current directory. Abstract and unnamed sockets,
.Xr socketpair 2 ,
and inherited descriptors are not path-mediated.
.Va allowAllUnixSockets
permits new Unix sockets without path checks. By default, new Unix sockets are
denied.
.Pp
Unix socket policy is unsupported on Windows and is rejected before launch.
.Sh SANDBOX MODEL
Landlock rules are tied to filesystem objects opened while the sandbox is
created, not to path strings. If an allowed directory is removed and the same
pathname is created again later, the new directory is a different filesystem
object and is not automatically allowed unless an allowed ancestor covers it.
Existing open file descriptors are not retroactively revoked.
.Pp
The traversal step gives deny rules snapshot semantics. Directories created
outside the sandbox after policy setup are not exposed merely because their
paths match a previous traversal result.
.Pp
On macOS,
.Nm
uses Seatbelt path rules.
.Pp
On Windows,
.Nm
uses a Less-Privileged AppContainer. The backend creates or reuses a
deterministic AppContainer profile and grants that AppContainer SID access to
the lowered read and write roots with Windows ACL entries. Because LPAC has no
broad filesystem read capability, Windows policies must use explicit read
allowlists; unrestricted read policy is rejected. AppContainer profiles and ACL
grants can persist after the sandboxed process exits.
.Sh OUTPUT
.Nm
prints landstrip failures as
.Sq field: value
lines on standard error, one line per field.
Fields with no value are omitted.
.Bd -literal -offset indent
reason: Other
file: policy.json
source: expected value at line 1 column 1
.Ed
The
.Va type
field is present when a policy or launch error has a subtype
(e.g.,
.Va filesystem ,
.Va network ,
.Va platform ,
.Va launch ,
.Va encoding ).
The
.Va reason
field is the error kind (e.g.
.Va Other ,
.Va LaunchFailed ,
.Va SetupFailed ,
.Va Usage ).
The
.Va file
field is present when a policy error is tied to a policy file. The
.Va program
field is present when
.Nm
could not start or encode a tool.
.Pp
Usage errors are not formatted responses; they are printed on standard error and
exit with status 2. Logs and sandboxed command output are not part of the formatted
response. Normal successful command execution does not print a response
because standard error belongs to landstrip and standard output belongs to the
sandboxed command.
.Pp
When
.Fl -error-fd Ar fd
is used,
.Nm
writes formatted response blocks to that file descriptor.
For example, Linux filesystem denials are emitted as:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
reason: AccessDenied
type: filesystem
file: /repo/out
operation: write
mechanism: seccomp
.Ed
This error stream is separate from the sandboxed command's standard output
and standard error.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
On success,
.Nm
is usually replaced by
.Ar command
and returns that command's exit status. When seccomp user notification is needed,
.Nm
supervises the sandboxed child and exits with the child's status. If policy
loading or sandbox setup fails,
.Nm
prints a formatted response and exits non-zero.
Usage errors exit with status 2.
